            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "Mold spore testing quantifies airborne mold concentrations and identifies specific species present. Air sampling collects spores on collection media sent to laboratory for analysis. Surface sampling tests visible mold growth or suspected contamination areas. Results compare indoor spore counts to outdoor baseline—healthy indoor air contains fewer mold spores than outdoor air. Elevated indoor counts indicate mold amplification from moisture problems, inadequate ventilation, or contaminated HVAC systems. Specific mold species identification determines health significance (some molds more allergenic or toxic than others) and likely moisture sources (different molds prefer different humidity and substrate conditions). Testing especially important if you notice visible mold growth, persistent musty odors, unexplained respiratory symptoms, or previous water damage. Results guide remediation efforts—addressing moisture sources, cleaning contaminated ductwork, improving ventilation, and installing UV lights preventing future biological growth."
